In article <36755k$dnk@jpunix.com>, Anonymous <nobody> wrote:
>Hi,
>  I am learning to program new things in C++, and have a few questions.
>I wrote a small piece of code that did some XOR'ing on encoded text I wanted
>to display on the screen.  It would be decoded and displayed.  How do I do this
>in C.  Is there someway I could do this in one .exe file?  When I messed
>around with it, I got the encoded message by running the program, piping the
>output and pasting it into my c code.  Is there a better way that actually
>works?

Generally, a single XOR in an encryption loop is relatively useless, unless
the keysize is big enough to be considered a one time pad.  

>Also, I see that there is c code to do CRC checks.  How do I integrate this
>into my C programs.  I want to CRC checks on my programs, to check to see if
>no changes were made.  And I want to store the CRC info in the program to check
>the program.  All help and advice is appreciated.  Thanks.

This is useless; CRC's can be easily forged.

Try leaving an email addr where you can be reached next time and you might
get someone to mail some code to you.

